oyal) coffer, attested in Anglo-Latin <i>cofferarius</i>. Compare   Coffer  . The modern English word <i>coffin</i> is a specialized development of this term, not attested until the 16th century.","History: Tristram Coffin came from Brixham, Devon, to Haverhill, MA, before 1647. An important line of his descendants is associated with Nantucket and Martha's Vineyard."],"variants":[{"name":"Coffer","meanings":["English: metonymic occupational name from Middle English <i>cofre</i>, <i>coffre</i>, <i>coffer</i> ‘box, chest’ (from Old French <i>cof(f)rehere</i>), used to denote a box or coffer maker (Old French <i>coffrier</i>), perhaps also for a treasurer.","Probably also an Americanized form of German   Kaufer   or <b>Kauffer</b>."]},{"name":"Coffing","meanings":["English: variant of   Coffin  ."]}]},{"name":"Maude","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Maud  , the usual spelling of the name in North America."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maude Coffin was born about 1092, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, her father, Coffin of Beacombe, was 33 and her mother, nn nn, was 28. She married Peter Le Moyne in 1115, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"ABT 1092–":"umbes 1092–Surnud","1092–Female":"1092–Surnud","1088–Male":"1088–Surnud","1118–Male":"1118–Surnud","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1065–Female":"1065–Surnud","1080":"1080","1118":"1118","1115":"1115","1088":"1088","1065":"1065","ABT 1118":"umbes 1118","ABT 1092":"umbes 1092","1060":"1060","1092":"1092","Powderidge,Devon,England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Beacombe,Devon,England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1092–":"noin 1092–Kuollut","1092–Female":"1092–Kuollut","1088–Male":"1088–Kuollut","1118–Male":"1118–Kuollut","1060–Male":"1060–Kuollut","1065–Fem